Comment in
    Curr Biol. 2021 Mar 8;31(5):R243-R246.

Sexual selection results in sex-specific characters like the conspicuously 
pigmented extension of the ventral tip of the caudal fin-the "sword"-in males of 
several species of Xiphophorus fishes. To uncover the genetic architecture 
underlying sword formation and to identify genes that are associated with its 
development, we characterized the sword transcriptional profile and combined it 
with genetic mapping approaches. Results showed that the male ornament of 
swordtails develops from a sexually non-dimorphic prepattern of transcription 
factors in the caudal fin. Among genes that constitute the exclusive sword 
transcriptome and are located in the genomic region associated with this trait 
we identify the potassium channel, Kcnh8, as a sword development gene. In 
addition to its neural function kcnh8 performs a known role in fin growth. These 
findings indicate that during evolution of swordtails a brain gene has been 
co-opted for an additional novel function in establishing a male ornament.

